Abrahamic "Security Patches": Analyzing Islam's theology as a "patch" on sequential Abrahamic faiths reveals its core tenets as corrective measures. From an Islamic perspective, the Torah had undergone Tahrif (corruption), with alleged alterations to prophecies and the improper veneration of figures like Ezra [32][37][38] . The Quran presents itself as a "guardian" to correct these errors [16][5] . Similarly, Islam addresses specific 7th-century Christian doctrines prevalent in Arabia, such as the Miaphysitism of the Ghassanids and the Nestorianism of the Lakhmids [35][65] . Islam's strict monotheism (Tawhid) and redefinition of prophethood directly address the Christian doctrine of the Trinity and the perceived deification of Jesus, which had been codified and enforced by Roman law centuries prior [52][37][34] . The Quran also offers radical corrections to Christian doctrine, such as the denial of the Crucifixion [73] .


Enki's Domain: The Sumerian descriptions of Enki's domain, the Abzu, are a mythological magnification of the actual geology of southern Iraq, specifically its high water table. The myths sanctify the environmental realities that made Sumerian civilization possible.


Body Generation: Many traditions describe beings (avatars, gods, angels) who can generate physical bodies. In nearly all cases, this form is a temporary interface. Examples include the Islamic Jinn, beings of "smokeless fire" who can manifest tangible forms [11][6] , and the Zoroastrian Dēws, malevolent spirits who shapeshift to deceive and harm [39][55] . A unique case is Jesus's post-resurrection body, which was a transformed physical form—tangible and able to eat, yet also capable of appearing in locked rooms and vanishing, indicating a new "glorified" state of existence [36][58][64] .



